<br>
I've also wanted to do a &quot;human future&quot; kind of story - something showing our species at a point when it faced with a decision of maturity vs. extinction.  In essence, a sort of &quot;2001&quot; meets David Brin's &quot;Earth&quot; story.  <br>
<br>
I've tried a few different concepts and so far this is what has emerged as a viable candidate.  I'd like your thoughts.<br>
<br>
---<br>
<br>
AD 2047: Almost forty years have passed since the last time the world was threatened by global war.  While some nations (the United States, China, and more recently Brazil) still dream of and struggle towards military dominance, the vast majority of nations in this era rely less on massive military might and more on cooperation with their neighbors for mutual defense, and thus are able to free up funds and manpower for more productive projects.  The African Reconstruction of the '20s is one example of such projects.  Some things still don't change though: Afghanistan is still suffering under fighting from its warlords and the Middle East remains embroiled in age-old hatreds.  Despite such setbacks, a very fragile <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Pax Humana</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> has begun to spread across the Earth.<br>
<br>
Human presence has begun to expand into the Solar System, at a rate that some consider too slow, and others consider too fast.  The advent of muon-fusion propulsion in the early '30s allows for spacecraft to reach the inner planets in weeks, and the outer worlds in months.  Colonies on the moon and Mars are just now emerging from the state of small, semi-isolated bases, though where the lunar bases are highly industry-centered and expanding, the Martian bases are more science-centered and have suffered funding losses in favour of new outposts in the Jovian moons.  <br>
<br>
A year before, a European probe to Saturn has reported an unexpected find: photos taken during a flyby of the Saturnian moon of Tethys have revealed what appears to be a crashed alien spacecraft on its surface.  Analysis of Pioneer, Voyager, and Cassini data suggests that the spacecraft is a recent arrival.   The United Nations Space Exploration Agency, currently the largest civilian space program (what national programs that survived to this date have either gone military only, such as the US or China, or have relegated themselves to near-Earth commercial efforts, such as Japan) hastily assembles an expedition to investigate the spacecraft.  Concerns from the UN Security Council lead for information about the alien vessel to be kept secret, though in this age of transparency this proves impossible.  Word leaks out to the world.<br>
<br>
The old superpowers see this as an opportunity - technology gleaned from the spacecraft might allow them to thwart the UN-backed &quot;peacesats&quot; that prevent each from gaining any significant advantage over each other or the world community, and the threat of &quot;alien invasion&quot; could be used to shut down the UNSEA and the gradual escape of their best and brightest in favour of the high frontier.  The Martian colonists see the alien spacecraft as a threat: if their plans for a self-sufficient and terraformed Mars have been delayed by the Jovian expansion, then this new expedition would kill future funding for them.  A cadre within the Martian colony concludes that the alien ship should be destroyed.  <br>
<br>
All of these plans are further complicated when it is revealed that the alien ship is no mere derelict: for the ship's crew is emerging from their cryogenic modules to discover that they are NOT where they were supposed to be... and the best hope they have of returning to space may lie with the strange bipedal invaders that have descended on them.<br>
<br>
---<br>
<br>
So ends the premise.  I'm a little unsure where the story should start: during the training phase, where we can introduce many of the human characters and human plotlines in a more &quot;leisurely&quot; format; or when the expedition is launched, to jump to the action faster and introduce the aliens sooner.  And of course the premise itself needs refining here and there, characters - in the expedition crew, back on Earth and Mars, and the alien crew - need to be fleshed out, and viewpoints decided upon.  The problem of subplots - how many and where - also needs to be considered.<br>
<br>
Your thoughts?<br>
<br>
